<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: MPs extend outside interests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR KENNETH Baker has used the nine months since he left the cabinet to
become a non-executive director of one blue-chip British company and an
adviser to two more.
The new register of members' interests, published yesterday, reveals that
the Conservative MP for the Surrey constituency of Mole Valley has joined
the board of Hanson, the multinational conglomerate.
A former minister for information technology, Mr Baker has also signed up as
an adviser to Cable and Wireless - the communications group chaired by his
former cabinet colleague Lord Young - and to ICL, the computer company.
His entry in the new register indicates that he has further supplemented his
portfolio of interests with directorships of Torrey Investments Inc and the
UK-Japan 2000 Group.
The register - which logs members' interests as at December 1 1992 - covers
nine classes of interest including directorships, sponsorships and
shareholdings as well as overseas visits where the cost has not been wholly
borne by the member or public funds.
Another former cabinet minister who has taken on a new outside interest is
Mr Tom King, previously defence secretary, who has become a director of
Electra Investment Trust.
Sir Norman Fowler, Conservative party chairman, became chairman of the
National House Building Council in June 1992. He continues to list a
directorship of Group 4 Securitas, which manages Britain's first privately
managed remand prison at Wolds in Humberside.
Sir Edward Heath, the former prime minister, has become a development
adviser to the China Investment and Development Fund and to Kleinwort Benson
China Management.
The number of MPs who are Names at Lloyd's of London, the troubled insurance
market, has fallen below 50, but still includes a number of ministers. Mr
Robert Banks, Conservative MP for Harrogate, notes for the first time that
he resigned from Lloyd's in 1989. Ms Jacqui Lait, Tory MP for Hastings and
Rye, indicates that she resigned from the market in December 1991.
Several MPs who have entered parliament since the last register was
published have declared ties to prominent companies.
Mr Barry Legg, Tory MP for Milton Keynes South West, is a consultant to
Hillsdown Holdings, the food group in the news recently for paying to
landscape a pond in the grounds of agriculture minister Mr John Gummer's
country house.
Others include Mr Bernard Jenkin (C Colchester North) who advises Legal and
General, the insurance group; Mr Peter Ainsworth (C East Surrey) who is a
consultant to SG Warburg Group; and Ms Judith Chaplin (C Newbury) who is a
consultant to Kleinwort Benson Securities and parliamentary adviser to the
Institute of Chartered Accountants.
Mr Peter Mandelson, Labour MP for Hartlepool, lists a trip to the Democratic
party convention in New York in August last year, at which the visitors'
programme was funded by Goldman Sachs, the US investment bank.
Among select committee chairmen, Sir Malcolm Thornton (education) has become
parliamentary consultant to the Littlewoods Organisation, while Sir Jerry
Wiggin (agriculture) continues to list consultancies to both British Sugar
and Sears. Mrs Marion Roe (health) has visited the Seychelles and Angola to
monitor elections.
In June, MPs backed new procedures to ensure those elected to the
chairmanships of Commons committees do not have business interests likely to
conflict with their parliamentary duties.
The register, which is available from HMSO, weighs in at 90 pages against
106 pages last January, and costs Pounds 1.35 less at Pounds 15.25.
</TEXT>
