<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Pressure grows for press laws
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CROSS-PARTY support for legislation to prohibit snooping, whether by
electronic surveillance, telephoto lenses or trespass, was mounting
yesterday following the widespread leaking of the Calcutt report on press
behaviour.
But MPs were divided over whether the government could or should set up a
powerful statutory press complaints tribunal with recourse to the courts -
reportedly the most formidable proposal by Sir David Calcutt QC.
The cabinet, which will discuss the report on Thursday, is divided on the
question. While Mr John Major, Mr Douglas Hurd and Mr Kenneth Clarke are
understood to favour action, others have doubts about the feasibility of
devising effective legislation.
For Labour, Ms Ann Clwyd, the shadow heritage secretary, expressed concern
that the leaks did not reveal any moves to balance right-of-reply provisions
with guarantees on the right to know.
Accusing some Fleet Street editors of 'hysterical' reactions to the report,
she said there was now much support across the country for statutory
restraints on the press.
She supported the private member's bill tabled by Mr Clive Soley, Labour MP
for Hammersmith, to set up a body to enforce the right of reply, targeted
chiefly at protecting private citizens.
But she expressed doubts about the possibility of effective legal restraints
without a freedom of information act to protect press freedoms.
Opinions among Conservatives were divided. Backbenchers have expressed anger
at press intrusions into the private lives of the royal family, and at the
coverage of recent events involving Mr Norman Lamont and Mr David Mellor.
But several have cautioned that the government must take care before
launching a vendetta against newspapers, many of which offered loyal support
to the party during the last general election.
Labour backbenchers are concerned, however, that the leaking of the Calcutt
conclusions might undermine Mr Soley's bill, which will have a second
reading on January 29. Mr Soley said he believed the leak would increase
cross-party backing for the bill.
Lord McGregor, chairman of the Press Complaints Commission, confirmed last
night that he had written to Sir David Calcutt in December saying that the
Princess of Wales had been 'participating in the provision of information
for tabloid editors about the state of her marriage.'
Lord McGregor said the actions of the Princess 'seriously embarrassed' the
commission, which had issued a statement condemning coverage of the royal
marriage after being assured by Buckingham Palace that the Princess was not
involved in any leak.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2711  Newspapers.
    P9651  Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
