<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: PM backs reform of teacher training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RADICAL reform of teacher training to switch responsibility away from
universities and colleges to schools is being pushed by Mr John Major as
part of his strategy to give new momentum to his domestic political agenda.
The prime minister is backing a return to proposals which would reduce
sharply the role of conventional teacher-training institutes in favour of
classroom-based experience in primary schools.
The plan is seen in Downing Street as the last piece in an policy jigsaw
designed to reverse irrevocably the 'progressive' and theory-based approach
to education adopted by successive governments during the 1960s and 1970s.
Mr Major considered the proposals at the two-day review at Chequers of his
domestic agenda which ended yesterday. Downing Street said afterwards that
renewed impetus for the government's education and health reforms were among
the key priorities.
Whitehall officials said Mr Major favoured the most radical of the options
being looked at by Mr John Patten, the education secretary, in a
wide-ranging review of the structure of teacher training.
It would in effect reverse the present system under which classroom
experience plays a relatively small part in an academically driven training
structure.
Last year Mr Patten appeared to backtrack on plans to shift more training of
secondary school teachers into the schools. He dropped plans to impose a
ceiling of one fifth on the college-based component of courses for the
postgraduate Certificate of Education and substituted instead a limit of one
third.
But the education secretary is said to be sympathetic to the idea of a
complete overhaul of the different system which applies to many primary
school teachers. Their training - based on the Bachelor of Education degree
 -is tied much more closely to courses at colleges and universities.
Such courses have long been a bete noire of those on the right of the Tory
party, where they are seen as responsible for the progressive trends in
education which have allegedly lowered standards in the nation's schools.
Mr Patten, who is expected to complete his review by the spring, is looking
at proposals which would switch the basic responsibility for primary school
training to individual schools or to groups of schools. Those specially
designed schools would then 'buy in' academic training by sending trainees
to the existing institutes.
Officials acknowledge that the scheme would create a range of problems, not
least because many of the country's primary schools, which total almost
20,000, are not large enough to take on training responsibilities.
But they insist that the problems are soluble. The screening of potential
candidates, for example, could be transferred from the existing institutes
to a centralised organisation. Training could then be focused on larger
primary schools which would receive extra funding or on groups of schools
operating in consortia.
</TEXT>
