<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Pledge on orders for railway stock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government last night announced steps to ensure that orders for new
railway rolling stock do not dry up because of the privatisation of British
Rail.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, told the all-party Commons transport
committee that new arrangements would be introduced before privatisation to
develop a market in leased rolling stock for BR and private operators. These
should ensure that new orders are placed before current orders for the new
Networker trains are completed in 1994.
Critics of rail privatisation have warned that a hiatus in orders for new
rolling stock because of the uncertainties over the future of BR could
damage the UK rolling stock industry, which employs 30,000 people.
Plans to allow BR to lease Pounds 150m of passenger coaches in 1994-95 and
1995-96 have been brought forward one year. This means that orders can be
placed in 1993-94, and BR has been asked to draw up a shopping list. A
discussion paper will set out options for creating a leasing market for
railway rolling stock once privatisation begins.
The key, according to ministers, will be to ensure that the risk on any
leases lies with the private sector. If the public sector bears the risk,
the investment must be counted against the public sector borrowing
requirement under UK public accounting rules.
Alternative routes for the high-speed rail link between London and the
Channel tunnel were submitted to Mr MacGregor by British Rail yesterday.
Mr MacGregor is expected to announce his preferred route in March and open a
period of public consultation.
</TEXT>
