<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Building boost predicted for next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CONSTRUCTION activity is expected to decline again this year
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
reaching a low point in the second half - but will rise modestly next year
as house building recovers with the slow improvement expected for the
economy, the joint forecasting committee for the construction industries
predicted yesterday.
The committee estimated that output had fallen 6 per cent last year to
Pounds 29.9bn at 1985 prices, and it expected a further 2 per cent fall this
year followed by a 1.5 per cent rise next year.
The forecast, published by Construction Forecasting &amp; Research, is the first
the committee has compiled independently of the National Economic
Development Office, which was abolished last month.
The forecast estimated that the value of new work fell 11 per cent between
1990 and 1992 to Pounds 17.8bn at 1985 prices.
The fall last year was estimated at 4.5 per cent compared with the 7.5 per
cent fall forecast six months ago. The change is due to a much higher
estimate of output for social housing and a revamped assessment of the
workload in the private industrial sector.
The committee pointed out, however, that expressing the reduction in the
volume of work in 1985 prices masked the figure for loss of work in current
prices. 'It is the latter which matters to firms large and small right
across the country, and it is estimated at 20 per cent in the past two
years,' it said. 'This highlights the extent to which the recession in the
industry has forced prices down.'
A further 4 per cent downturn in new work was forecast for this year, with
another considerable fall in private non-residential construction only
partly offset by increases in housing and public non-housing output. New
work was predicted to rise by 1 per cent next year based on further
increases in housing output.
The committee commented that the sole measure in the government's Autumn
Statement that benefited construction was the release of Pounds 750m to
housing associations to buy 16,000 homes by the end of the financial year.
The forecasts for this year show variations between construction sectors.
Public and private housing output were both predicted to rise 10 per cent
this year and 11 per cent and 12 per cent respectively next year.
The outlook for private commercial work remained gloomy, the committee
believed, mainly because of the surplus of offices.
Construction Forecasts, Winter 1992. Construction Forecasting &amp; Research,
Princes House, 39 Kingsway, London WC2B 6TP. Pounds 50.
</TEXT>
