<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Change proposed for workplace childcare
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROVISION of childcare by employers remains scarce, but there may be a trend
towards targeting it according to the needs of the business, the independent
research group Incomes Data Services suggests.
Its study of 22 organisations says many employers allocate childcare places
on a first-come-first-served basis. It points out that this has drawbacks:
'Nursery provision is expensive and only a limited number of places will be
available. From the employer's viewpoint it is preferable to target this
expensive benefit where it would have the most impact.' The study says
Midland Bank allocates nursery places according to staff skills while
Sainsbury, the supermarket chain, gives priority to retail staff.
Employers also look at social factors such as the needs of single or
disabled parents.
IDS says that employers have a variety of approaches, which 'range from
full-scale workplace nurseries and childcare allowances to holiday
playschemes for school-age children and some referral services to help
working parents identify suitable childcare facilities'.
Childcare. IDS, 193 St John St, London EC1V 4LS. By subscription.
</TEXT>
