<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Warning on funds for elderly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FUNDING problems in providing residential care for the elderly are likely to
become 'significantly worse' when the government's community care reforms
are introduced in April, the charity Methodist Homes for the Aged said
yesterday.
Methodist Homes, one of Britain's biggest charitable providers of
residential care, warned that 'both the quality and the availability of
appropriate care may be under threat' from lack of funding.
Funding through social security payments to accommodate elderly people in
residential homes has risen from Pounds 10m in 1979 to about Pounds 2.5bn.
Methodist Homes says government support has nevertheless not kept pace with
actual care costs. The charity spends Pounds 400,000 a year subsidising
social-security-funded residents in its homes.
Methodist Homes said the problem was likely to worsen after April, when
councils become responsible for assessing individuals' care needs. There
will be greater emphasis on providing domiciliary rather than residential
care.
'Some local authorities have indicated that charges for residential care
should be in line with income support levels, despite the fact that
residential care in the future is likely to be reserved for more dependent
elderly people who will need a higher level of care,' said Mr David Wigley,
chief executive of Methodist Homes.
'Other local authorities are indicating that they will be prepared to pay
higher charges, but still short of the true cost of providing care for very
dependent people.'
Methodist Homes says it will not drop its standards of care but fears
private sector providers may be forced to. The charity says the need to
continue subsidising residents means it will abandon plans to build new
facilities unless it can raise an additional Pounds 3m over the next three
years. homes in
</TEXT>
