<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Court plea on pit pay fails
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINERS FROM two of the 10 collieries that are closing under the government's
pit closure programme lost a court action yesterday to win bonuses on top of
basic pay, Richard Donkin writes.
The case was brought by the Union of Democratic Mineworkers on behalf of
miners at Silverhill and Cotgrave pits in Nottinghamshire, where coal
production has stopped.
The union argued that miners at the two pits, and at eight other collieries
facing closure, should be given bonus payments and shift allowances as well
as basic pay for the period they have been laid off.
The union believed that, had the court action been successful, miners at all
10 pits could have claimed up to Pounds 2,000 in back pay from the time
production stopped last year.
The payments would not have affected redundancy terms because British Coal
has agreed to base calculations on the period up to the closure
announcements in October, when men would have been receiving bonuses.
Mr David Prendergast, UDM vice-president, said the union was disappointed by
the decision 'and we are considering grounds for appeal'.
</TEXT>
