<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Court told of 'simple' Pounds 5.2m Guinness theft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR THOMAS Ward, the US lawyer and former Guinness director, laid the ground
for the theft of Pounds 5.2m from the company after its successful takeover
bid for Distillers in 1986, an Old Bailey jury heard yesterday.
Opening the prosecution at the start of the final Guinness trial, Mr Victor
Temple alleged that Mr Ward sought and obtained the co-operation of Mr
Ernest Saunders, the former Guinness chairman and chief executive, who lent
his direct assistance to the dishonest enterprise.
Mr Ward faces one charge of stealing Pounds 5.2m from Guinness and single
charges of false accounting and procuring the execution of a valuable
security in relation to the alleged theft. He denies all the charges.
Mr Temple said Mr Ward and Mr Saunders had been friends and confidants for a
number of years. Mr Ward was Mr Saunders' principal adviser and had joined
the Guinness board in January 1985.
After Guinness won its bitter takeover battle with Argyll to take control of
Distillers, the company had to pay its advisers.
Mr Temple said the chances that any particular invoice would be checked were
remote and both Mr Ward and Mr Saunders were sufficiently powerful to be
able to deflect any queries that might arise.
This allowed the two men, doubtless motivated by greed, to put into effect a
simple, clever and effective joint enterprise to steal the Pounds 5.2m, he
said.
Through the submission of a false invoice the money was paid to Marketing
and Acquisition Consultants, a Jersey-based company controlled by Mr Ward.
Guinness's strategy during the takeover was decided by a committee of three
directors - Mr Saunders, Mr Ward and Mr Olivier Roux, the company's finance
director.
Mr Temple said Mr Roux would appear as the prosecution's principal witness.
There would be a 'head-on clash' between his evidence and Mr Ward's version
of events, he told the jury.
The trial, which is expected to last about three months, continues today.
</TEXT>
