<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Invesco MIM expects to face disciplinary process
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESCO MIM, the fund management company, is under investigation by
regulators and expects to face disciplinary proceedings.
In a letter sent yesterday to shareholders in City and Commercial Investment
Trust, an investment trust managed by Invesco MIM, the directors of the
trust said: 'The directors of City and Commercial. . . have discussed with
Invesco MIM an investigation which the Investment Management Regulatory
Organisation (Imro) is undertaking with Invesco MIM. The outcome of this
inquiry is unknown but it is considered likely that it will result in some
form of disciplinary process against Invesco MIM.'
City and Commercial shareholders are shortly to approve a reorganisation of
the investment trust, which is approaching its wind-up date. The
investigation and probable disciplinary proceedings are considered material
information which must be given to shareholders.
The information was not disclosed in the original prospectus sent to
shareholders in December, but City and Commercial's directors decided to
release the information after taking legal advice.
Officials at Invesco MIM would not comment yesterday. The investigation is
believed to involve a general review of all the company's internal
procedures and controls, and to have begun about a year ago.
Imro is believed to have notified Invesco MIM in the second half of last
year that it was likely to be the subject of disciplinary proceedings.
In October 1991 Invesco MIM was fined Pounds 75,000 by Imro for poor
administration of personal equity plans. It is also the subject of a writ by
trustees of the Mirror Group Newspapers pension scheme, a portion of whose
assets it managed, in connection with the disappearance of more than Pounds
11m in assets via unusual stock lending deals.
Last autumn Invesco MIM became the first UK fund manager to pay compensation
to shareholders for mismanagement of an investment trust in its charge. It
paid Pounds 9.5m to shareholders in Drayton Consolidated Investment Trust.
The compensation stemmed from Invesco MIM's decision to invest Pounds 43m in
a troubled company and its failure to disclose the extent of that investment
to Drayton's shareholders and directors.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Invesco MIM.
</CO>
