<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Rules change will help film industry cut tax bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FILM-MAKERS will be be allowed to apply new techniques of accounting to help
reduce their tax bills under guidelines issued by the Inland Revenue
yesterday.
An updated statement of practice for the film industry shows that it will be
able to write off costs against tax far more quickly than current
regulations permit, and to improve cashflow.
The statement lays down rules first promised in the 1992 Budget. They are
designed to boost the British film industry and to bring it in line with the
more generous tax allowances permitted in other countries.
It provides details of what expenses will be eligible for accelerated
relief, and the time limits on applying for tax relief under the new
arrangements.
The statement permits pre-production or preliminary expenses to be written
off pound-for-pound against tax as they are incurred.
Previously these could be set against tax only when a decision had been
taken on whether a film would be made, which could be one or more tax years
later.
To be eligible these preliminary expenses must be reasonably said to have
been made to enable a decision to be taken on whether or not to go ahead
with the film.
The statement also allows film companies to write off all production costs
in three years at 33.3 per cent a year. That compares with the previous 25
per cent a year of remaining costs for capital expenditure, and over the
life of the film for revenue costs.
Film companies wishing to adopt the new methods must make a claim in writing
to the local inspector of taxes within two years of the completion of the
film.
To be eligible films must be qualified as British or EC-based by the
Department of National Heritage under the 1985 Films Act.
The film industry has in the past said that it is at a disadvantage to other
sectors because it has to incur so many costs long before it receives the
revenues on films. That has made it extremely difficult for independent
companies to operate.
</TEXT>
