<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Business clients still critical of banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE are still 'substantial weaknesses' in the relationship between banks
and their small-business customers, says a survey published yesterday by the
Forum of Private Business, the lobby group.
Poor communication between banks and small businesses may make it difficult
for enterprises to raise funds for expansion when the economy recovers,
according to the survey of more than 6,000 businesses.
Forty per cent of business owners said the banks did not understand small
companies.
Scottish banks won a more favourable rating from their customers than their
English counterparts. Barclays won the highest marks among the English
banks, while Lloyds scored lowest.
The survey by Nottingham University said banks were starting to
differentiate their services more. It found no backing for claims that banks
had not passed on the benefit of cuts in base rates to small companies.
In spite of banks' efforts to improve relations with small companies by
drawing up charters or codes of practice, there was no change in the issues
highest on businesses' concerns - account charges, interest rates and the
need to provide collateral.
Small Businesses and Their Banks. Report Pounds 800, summary Pounds 3.50.
0565 634467.
