<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Resistance to job relocation 'growing'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEE resistance to job relocation is growing, mainly because of the
difficulties of selling homes and the reluctance of partners to give up
their jobs and move, according to a survey published yesterday.
Nearly 40 per cent of the 251 companies surveyed said a working spouse
'presented a key inhibitor to relocation'. A third mentioned concern about
children's education and just more than a quarter quoted family ties and
roots as reasons for reluctance to move with the company.
Ms Sue Shortland, head of the Confederation of British Industry's relocation
group, said: 'The issue of the working partner will increase with more women
working and more dual-income families.'
She added that it was not only the temporary loss of income that caused
problems but also the damage to the partner's career, promotion and income
potential.
The current property price slump is the most serious barrier to relocation.
As many as 44 per cent of the sample said inability to sell their home
inhibited them from being moved to another part of the country by their
employer.
The survey, published by the CBI and Black Horse Relocation Services,
suggests that employers are not doing all they can to deal with the
relocation problems of their workers. While four out of five companies
sampled said they were trying to resolve the difficulties of moving home
with financial assistance, fewer than a third were doing anything to help
working partners find a new job.
When asked how employees' needs for relocation support would change in the
next three years, as many as 24 per cent said the requirements of working
spouses would become more important while 10 per cent mentioned the slump in
the property market and a further 7 per cent 'negative equity problems'.
More than half of the companies surveyed were in the manufacturing sector.
</TEXT>
