<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / IADB launches Latin America investment fund
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The InterAmerican Development Bank yesterday launched its much-delayed
Multilateral Investment Fund to promote private sector investment, financial
market deregulation and other economic reforms in Latin America, writes
Nancy Dunne.
President George Bush proposed a Dollars 1.5bn fund in June 1990 as part of
his Enterprise for the Americas Initiative. He envisaged that the US, EC and
Japan would each give Dollars 500m over five years to get the fund
established. Contributions, however, have totalled less than Dollars 1.26bn.
Although Japan has pledged its Dollars 500m, Europe has been less generous.
Spain is contributing Dollars 50m, Germany Dollars 30m, Italy Dollars 30m,
France Dollars 15m, Portugal Dollars 4m.
The US Congress has authorised Dollars 90m for the first year, rather than
the Dollars 100m requested by the president. Latin American countries are
contributing the rest.
The fund will have three separate facilities. One will provide technical
assistance to identify and implement policy changes needed to boost the
private sector. A 'human resources' facility will lift productivity by
funding education and worker retraining programmes. Another facility will
establish a revolving fund to make loans and equity investments in support
of micro- and small-business enterprises run by women, minorities and the
poor.
