<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / US Marines in crackdown on Somali gun bazaar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NAIROBI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US MARINES closed down a big gun bazaar in Mogadishu yesterday, continuing
an unofficial policy of arms reduction in the chaotic country.
About 900 Marines in armoured vehicles sealed off the sprawling Bakara
market, which sprang up after the overthrow of President Mohamed Siad Barre
two years ago. 'We have seized a large number of weapons,' said Major Ken
Roberts. 'We feel we have taken a significant number of weapons off the
streets and out of the market.'
The Marines' action came as Somali warlords agreed in Addis Ababa to declare
a ceasefire and start stripping their militias of heavy weapons, a move
which further strengthened the tentative peace agreement taking shape in the
Ethiopian capital.
Although the ceasefire is unlikely to end fighting in Somalia - rival gunmen
in Mogadishu clashed for about half an hour last night - the agreement could
mark a significant step down the long road to peace.
At the UN-sponsored talks in Addis Ababa 15 clan-based factions committed
themselves to handing over all heavy weapons to a monitoring group, to be
composed of UN troops, until a legitimate Somali government is formed.
The warlords and faction leaders also agreed to move militias into camps
outside the main towns by March 1 in preparation for complete disarmament;
to establish a register for all civilian weapons; to free all political
prisoners; and return confiscated property to rightful owners.
Delegates have already agreed to convene a national reconciliation
conference on March 15 which will write a national charter and create an
interim assembly and government. Talks were still deadlocked yesterday,
however, on who should attend the conference, which will have extraordinary
power to chart Somalia's political future, including the thorny issue of
choosing an interim president.
Diplomats and observers in Addis Ababa say they have sensed a new mood of
realism among the warlords in the past five days. They say the warlords are
increasingly aware their power, based on monopoly of heavy weapons and food
aid, is disintegrating.
Intensified efforts by foreign troops at what US officials describe as 'arms
reduction,' rather than disarmament which has been publicly ruled out by
Washington, have clipped the wings of the militia bosses.
Many Somalis, however, have criticised the way the United Nations has
allowed the warlords to tie up a deal aimed at preserving their illegitimate
power rather than opening up the peace process to clan elders, intellectuals
and exiled politicians. They question whether any deal struck by
increasingly desperate faction leaders will be able to deliver a lasting
solution to the country's woes.
</TEXT>
