<DATE>930112
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Japanese companies 'feel overstaffed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY Japanese companies believe they are overstaffed, according to an
official survey published yesterday, raising the possibility that the
Japanese social contract based on lifetime employment could come under
strain.
The survey of 18 industries, conducted last month by the Ministry of Labour,
found that the steel, electrical appliances, securities and information
service industries felt that they had too many staff on their payrolls.
This mounting concern about overstaffing marks a significant shift in
Japanese employers' attitudes. Six months ago, most employers were concerned
that Japan's slowing birthrate was creating a structural labour shortage by
reducing the rate of growth of the labour force to less than 1 per cent a
year.
However, senior officials at the ministry believe some companies may soon be
forced into taking drastic action to cut employment costs, including
compulsory retirement programmes for older workers, if the economic downturn
persists beyond the first three months of the year.
This raises the prospects of more Japanese companies in hard-pressed sectors
such as electronics following the lead of companies such as Pioneer, the
audio equipment maker, which recently announced plans for the early
retirement of a small group of managers over the age of 50.
Although moves such as Pioneer's may make only a small dent in employment
costs, they send a powerful message to younger workers that their future
security is no longer automatically guaranteed.
Over the past few months most Japanese companies have deployed a variety of
measures to reduce employment costs without resorting to redundancies,
including cutting bonuses and overtime hours, freezing recruitment and
laying off part-time workers.
However, with most companies facing their third year of declining profits,
many are under pressure to improve profitability through a more aggressive
approach to cutting employment costs.
Nevertheless Japanese companies are not about to adopt western methods of
management which can involve sharp cuts in employment to reduce costs during
a recession.
</TEXT>
