<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Inquiry to study tighter rules on oil tanker routes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SEPARATE inquiry into the Braer disaster is to consider stricter
regulation of oil tanker movements off the UK coast in order to avoid a
repetition of the environmental damage caused after the vessel ran aground
in the Shetland Islands last week.
The government said yesterday that Lord Donaldson, former Master of the
Rolls, will head the inquiry. The marine accident investigation branch of
the Department of Transport has already begun to investigate the causes of
the disaster.
The Braer continued to be battered by hurricane-force storms yesterday,
which caused further damage to more than half of the vessel's oil tanks
which were all leaking heavily into the sea. Hopes of recovering any of the
Braer's oil before it caused further pollution were diminishing last night
as storms continued.
Captain Geert Koffeman of Smit Tak, the Dutch salvage company handling the
Braer, said: 'We can never be sure we will recover any oil. There is no
guarantee, but we are doing our best.' He indicated that the ship could
break up within days in some of the worst weather conditions experienced in
the Shetland Islands.
The Department of Transport's Marine Pollution Control Centre said it had
still received no reports of major quantities of oil coming ashore.
The Royal Society for the Protection of Birds said that important breeding
colonies for shag and black guillemot could be wiped out by the oil spill.
The tanker's US-based operator, Bergvall and Hudner, yesterday promised a
'substantial' contribution to the wildlife clean-up costs on the Shetland
Islands. Company officials believe the bill for the clean-up could run into
'hundreds of thousands of pounds'.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, and Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary,
underlined in the House of Commons the government's determination to ensure
that the 'polluter pays'.
Mr MacGregor said the Donaldson inquiry has been called 'to advise whether
further measures are appropriate and feasible to protect the UK coastline
from pollution from merchant shipping. Due consideration should be given to
the international and economic implications of any new measures'. He made a
cautious response to demands for unilateral action by the UK to restrict oil
tanker movements in the English channel and other areas where a collision or
other accident would be likely to have disastrous consequences.
While stressing that the Donaldson inquiry would be free to make the
recommendations it thought appropriate he suggested that concerted action
based on an international agreement was likely to produce the most effective
results. Mr MacGregor envisaged that Lord Donaldson would be joined by
specialist assessors in conducting the inquiry, and said that, if necessary,
they would be able to make an interim report on proposals requiring urgent
implementation.
Mr John Prescott, shadow transport secretary, said it should be made clear
to all oil companies and carriers of hazardous materials that it was
'totally unacceptable' for them to take dangerous routes which, while
cheaper and quicker in commercial terms, were potentially more damaging and
dangerous.
In a renewed attack on the wide use of flags of convenience, Mr Prescott
accused some countries of 'prostituting their flags for a few pieces of
silver' to enable shipowners 'to use second rate vessels, with second rate
crews, following second rate practices'.
Oil market steadier despite Opec worries, Page 26
</TEXT>
