<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / UN condemns Baghdad's defiance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN Security Council early today condemned Iraq's removal by force of
military equipment from the Kuwaiti side of the demilitarised zone and
demanded its immediate return for destruction.
In a strongly-worded statement, the council called yesterday's Iraqi
intrusion into Kuwaiti territory - the second in two days - a 'direct
challenge' to the UN and a clear-cut defiance of the world body.
It warned Baghdad of 'the serious consequences that will flow from such
continued defiance' of UN mandates. However, the UN's condemnation came in
the form of a non-binding statement by Mr Yoshio Hatano of Japan, the
current UN president, and no fresh punishment of Iraq was announced.
The statement was read out by Mr Hatano after it was approved, then revised
and approved again in closed-door deliberations.
The Security Council meeting followed warnings from Mr Boutros Boutros
Ghali, the UN secretary general, that violations and threats against Kuwait
could not be tolerated and demands from the US for 'steps that can be taken
to ensure that Iraq complies with UN resolutions'.
A UN spokesman in Kuwait said about 150 Iraqis had crossed the border
yesterday and dismantled several warehouses. Up to 500 had been involved in
the seizure of arms from four weapons bunkers on Sunday. Iraqi president
Saddam Hussein is also defying the UN by refusing to allow UN inspectors to
fly to Baghdad to continue their search for weapons of mass destruction.
While the UN talks were under way, there were indications of further
movements of Iraqi missiles in both the northern and southern allied-imposed
no-fly zones in Iraq.
But Mr Robert Gates, head of the Central Intelligence Agency, said it was
too early to decide whether the weapons still threatened allied aircraft.
The US has already threatened military action if Mr Saddam again orders
surface-to-air missiles and radars into the southern air exclusion zone
below the 32nd parallel.
Last night's UN statement noted a stipulation last November that military
equipment in six bunkers in the former Iraqi naval base at Umm Qasr, in
Kuwaiti territory, should be destroyed by or under the supervision of the UN
Iraq-Kuwait Observation Mission (Unikom).
The council demanded that any future Iraqi retrieval mission should meet the
terms set out by Mr Hatano last Friday.
The statement also affirmed the council's guarantee of the inviolability of
the Iraq-Kuwait boundary recently redrawn by a UN commission.
The council stressed that Unikom facilities at Camp Khor should be inviolate
and subject to the exclusive control and authority of the UN.
The council asked Mr Boutros Ghali to explore urgently possibilities for
restoring Unikom to full strength and consider 'in an emergency such as
this' the need for rapid reinforcement as well as any other suggestions to
enhance the effectiveness of the mission.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, warned that he was 'losing patience' with
Baghdad. Officials said he would not rule out a military response to the
latest Iraqi actions. He will discuss the options with other ministers this
morning. But UK officials played down suggestions of imminent strikes
against Iraqi forces, stressing that any action would be agreed first at the
UN.
Baghdad yesterday maintained its defiant public stance, with Mr Ali Hassan
al-Majeed, defence minister, insisting that Iraq would free itself from the
no-fly zones. He pledged that Iraq's national sovereignty would be fully
reclaimed and US military aggression defeated.
Saddam pushes UN resolve to the limit Page 4
MPs hear of heavy sales to Iraq Page 9
</TEXT>
