<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 93 / Big pension law changes unlikely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's pension law review committee is unlikely to recommend
sweeping changes that might deter employers from making pension provision,
the committee's chairman signalled yesterday.
Professor Roy Goode also said he hoped to mitigate the effects of tougher
pension regulation by recommending simplification of the many, often
conflicting, regulations that govern occupational pensions.
'The consensus expressed across the whole range of respondents to our
consultative paper was a desire to see to it that the baby is not thrown out
with the bath water,' Prof Goode said in an interview with the Financial
Times. Pension scheme members as well as sponsors had expressed that view,
he said.
The committee was unlikely to recommend, however, that the current regime
remains unchanged.
As a result of responses to its initial paper, issued last autumn, he added,
the committee had expanded its review to include ways to simplify the
administrative burden for employers. The pensions industry has long
complained about the tax treatment for schemes which contract out of the
State Earnings Related Pension Scheme.
The committee is unlikely to take the line urged by employers' groups which
would give employers unequivocal use of pension fund surpluses. Prof Goode
said the panel might take the view that surpluses belonged neither to
employers nor scheme members but served to guarantee payment of promised
benefits.
The committee is also examining ways to guarantee the enforceability of
trust law which currently governs pension fund administration.
Thorny questions for pension group, Page 8
