<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / School for young blacks in jeopardy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN inner-city educational project that has successfully motivated young
black people to study and obtain qualifications is fighting for survival
because of financial problems.
A total of 300 pupils aged between eight and 18 are studying voluntarily
during evenings, weekends and holidays at the Chapeltown and Harehills
Assisted Learning Computer School in Leeds, and a further 400 are waiting
for a place.
The school, set up in 1987 by Mr Brainard Braimah, a Ghanian teacher, to
tackle low educational achievement among local black children, has seen four
of its former students go to university and dozens obtain GCSEs.
The winding-up last year of the Leeds Task Force, a government inner-city
initiative, cost the school its main source of funding.
A final grant of pounds 25,000 - matched by equal sums from Leeds City
Action Team and the city's Training and Enterprise Council - was expected to
last until March 31, but will be used up by next month, leaving the school
in urgent need of pounds 7,000 to survive until April and uncertain of its
funding next year.
Mr Braimah last week held discussions with the City Action Team, which
coordinates government department's inner-city efforts in Leeds and Bradford
and later this month will meet the Tec. But he is not hopeful they will be
able to fill the gap.
Income generated by the school's commercial training wing is not yet
sufficient to replace grant aid, he says. Leeds City Council and the Home
Office already provide support, and Unisys, the computer company, has
donated pounds 100,000 of equipment and free maintenance.
Mr Braimah believes young black people underperform educationally because of
low expectations and lack of encouragement, home support and role models.
The school combines computer-based lessons in maths, English and science
with more traditional methods - pupils learn tables and are set homework.
Computer games are not allowed.
'This project does not just take these youngsters off the streets but lets
them realise the responsibility they owe to society,' he said.
The project has four full-time staff including Mr Braimah and 10 part-time
teachers. All pupils attend one formal two-hour tuition session a week and
can work outside school hours. During school holidays, says Mr Bramiah, many
are queueing outside when the doors open.
The City Action Team and Leeds Tec said funding for next year had not yet
been determined, but both praised the school.
Mr Jeremy Walker, chairman of the City Action Team, said: 'They have been
particularly impressive in the way in which they appear to be able to
motivate young people to improve their education performance.'
</TEXT>
