<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / Storms block Shetland salvage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HEAVY seas and high winds around Shetland again blocked attempts to remove
the oil remaining on the tanker Braer yesterday and hampered efforts to deal
with the pollution caused by the disaster.
Although the ship has not broken apart, salvage specialists believe this
will eventually happen.
Experts who flew over the tanker yesterday now believe that no further oil
is leaking from the vessel, which may still contain as much as half of its
84,000-tonne cargo. But oil is still spreading northwards for about 25 miles
up the west coast of the main Shetland island.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, and Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary,
will both make statements to the Commons about the disaster today.
About 600 people living within a two-mile radius of the wreck will have
liver and respiratory checks this week after fears that pollution from the
Braer may be toxic, and protective masks were yesterday issued to crofters
living near the scene.
Yesterday Shetland salmon farmers received a boost when the supermarket
group Safeway said it would continue to buy farmed Shetland salmon after a
company official visited fish farms and environmental specialists on the
islands.
Last Friday Marks and Spencer announced that it would stop buying Shetland
salmon as 'a temporary precautionary measure'. Other food retailers are
monitoring the situation.
The Shetland salmon farming industry is one of the sectors of the islands'
economy most threatened by the disaster.
Since Friday the salmon farmers have been prohibited from harvesting salmon
in a 400 square mile area under a ban ordered by the Scottish Office. The
ban, which also covers the catching of sea fish, was announced just after
the islands' fishing and fish-farming organisations had declared their own
ban.
There are 16 salmon farms in the area covered by the ban, accounting for
about a quarter of Shetland's salmon production which last year totalled
10,000 tonnes.
Shetland council said yesterday that it was retaining the solicitors
Penningtons to represent it in dealing with legal issues arising from the
incident. The council has initiated no legal action so far.
High winds caused by the near-record atmospheric depression between
north-west Scotland and Iceland battered Britain yesterday.
At Renfrew in Scotland the River Clyde burst its banks at high tide and
flooding also hit Lochgilphead and Tarbert in Argyll. Coastguards expected
force 12 storms to hit the area around Orkney and Shetland.
Other badly hit areas were Oxfordshire, Sussex, Surrey, Kent, Hampshire and
Somerset, while in Essex beaches and seafronts were closed at Jaywick Sands
and Southend.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1311  Crude Petroleum and Natural Gas.
    P4499  Water Transportation Services, NEC.
    P9511  Air, Water, and Solid Waste Management.
</IN>
<XX>
