<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / Managers' training 'insufficient'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE than 50 per cent of managers say they receive insufficient training, a
survey published today by the Institute of Management says.
The report, which the institute says is the most comprehensive to date, is
based on a survey of training undergone by more than 2,000 managers. The
institute undertook the research with the Economic and Social Research
Council.
Concern has been expressed recently by a number of organisations, including
the Confederation of British Industry, about the quality and quantity of
training for managers and supervisors in the UK. Un-favourable comparisons
have been drawn with other countries such as Germany.
The study concludes that training of managers should be directed at reaching
national standards.
The report, by Professor Peter Warr of the University of Sheffield, says 88
per cent of managers undertook some training in 1991, with an average of
five days a year on work-time training and three days training during their
own time, including home study.
Many managers had little opportunity to train, the survey says. One third of
the managers surveyed said their organisation did not have a formal training
policy, and one in eight received no training in 1991.
Managers were convinced of the business case for more training - 81 per cent
said they would be more effective if they had had more training.
The survey reinforces the belief of many involved in training, including the
Training and Enterprise Councils, that government efforts to improve
training should be directed at small companies.
The survey shows that managers in companies employing fewer than 25 people
were the least likely to have had training in work time and had the most
negative attitudes to it.
Training for Managers. IM Books, Burston Distribution Services, Unit 2a,
Newbridge Trading Estate, Newbridge Close, Whitby Road, Bristol BS4 4AX.
Pounds 15 for IM members, Pounds 30 non-members.
</TEXT>
