<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / Fowler joins Major in tax warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Norman Fowler, the Conservative party chairman, yesterday joined Mr John
Major, the prime minister, in cautioning against growing calls for the
government to increase taxes to tackle its mounting deficit.
In an ITV television interview the Conservative party chairman appeared to
side with the growing number of Tory MPs who have expressed disquiet at
arguments by Lord Howe, the former chancellor, that tax rises may be
necessary and inevitable.
'The Conservative party is and remains the party of low taxation,' he said.
Mr Major last week also appeared to reject increases in income tax or value
added tax in an BBC interview with Sir David Frost.
Sir Norman's comments came after the end of Mr Norman Lamont's traditional
two-day brainstorming session at the Kent country house of Chevening where
the chancellor met officials to discuss options for the coming budget.
The party chairman was en route to a similar meeting at Chequers where Mr
Major was yesterday holding talks with senior Downing Street policy staff.
The meeting reviewed ways of adding momentum to the government's programme
and finding ways of highlighting its underlying philosophy.
Senior Conservative Central Office officials are due at Chequers today to
discuss a radical reorganisation of the party and plans for tackling an
overdraft nearing Pounds 20m. Two reviews of the party's organisation - one
of professional employees, the other of the voluntary section - are also on
the agenda.
An announcement of a comprehensive restructuring of the party is due early
in February. Under plans announced last week by Mr Paul Judge, the new
Central Office director-general, annual overspending running at Pounds 5m is
to be brought into balance by 1996.
The reforms include the loss of up to 60 professional staff at the Smith
Square headquarters and regional offices.
A scheme devised by Sir Basil Feldman, chairman of the National Union of
Conservative Associations, the party's voluntary wing, also envisages the
creation of a new board of management for the party as part of an overhaul
of its command structures.
Members of the Charter movement, a pressure group for more internal
democracy in the party, have campaigned for constituency associations to
have the right to elect the chairman of the board.
A senior official said last night there was no likelihood of the suggestion
being adopted as it was crucial the party chairman be appointed by the party
leader and had his or her confidence. 'There are only about two Charter
supporters on the National Union executive. That amounts to about 150 people
in all,' he said.
</TEXT>
