<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / Legislation 'threat to equal pay'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE gap between men's and women's pay could widen because of the
government's Employment Bill, the Equal Opportunities Commission says today
in a critical review of the proposed legislation.
Ms Joanna Foster, who chairs the commission, said: 'In our view, the
employment bill has enormous implications for women at work.' She added that
government consultation had been inadequate given the significance of the
legislation.
Ms Foster, who has had several public disagreements with Mrs Gillian
Shephard, employment minister, will stand down as chair of the commission
later this year.
The commission said three clauses, including one providing for maternity
rights and another abolishing wages councils, gave most cause for concern.
It warned that the clause on maternity rights was inadequate and might not
fully comply with European Community law, and that it would make a scheme
which was already too complicated still more complex.
