<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / Showdown in the Last Chance Saloon: Raymond Snoddy examines
the implications of the Calcutt report on regulating the press
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE political battle to determine where the line should be drawn between
press freedom and individual privacy started in earnest yesterday.
According to widespread leaks in Sunday's national newspapers Sir David
Calcutt QC, in his report on press behaviour, has decided self-regulation of
the press has failed and that tough action should be taken, including fines
and a statutory press complaints tribunal.
Although there was no official confirmation yesterday, those who gave
evidence to Sir David and have seen parts of the report believe the
newspapers were broadly correct.
Sir David, whose original report on the press and privacy was published in
June 1990, was asked to look at how the new Press Complaints Commission -
whose establishment he recommended - was working.
Ironically, Sir David's second report on the press was called for by Mr
David Mellor when national heritage secretary - before his political career
was engulfed by tabloid headlines. The months in which Sir David took
evidence coincided with a long hot summer of controversial articles about
the personal lives not only of Mr Mellor and an actress, but also of members
of the royal family.
The reported Calcutt recommendations follow closely his recipe in the
original report for what should happen if self-regulation failed. There
would be substantial fines for newspapers breaching a statutory code of
conduct implemented by a press complaints tribunal. The chairman of such a
tribunal, replacing the complaints commission, would be a judge, sitting
with two lay assessors. These would amount to the most draconian measures
taken against the British press in modern times.
Under the proposals there would be new criminal offences covering physical
intrusion, electronic eavesdropping and taking long-distance photographs of
people who are on private property. These proposals were in the original
report but not implemented.
The leaks came after the report was delivered on Friday to Mr Peter Brooke,
national heritage secretary, and appear to be the work of journalistic
contacts with political sources, rather than a government move to discredit
the proposals. Mr Brooke's officials declined to comment yesterday.
The press has been worried for some months about what Sir David would
recommend. The first signs that the proposals might be tougher than expected
came just before Christmas when a small group from the complaints commission
was shown two chapters. The group was not told of Sir David's findings, only
allowed to check the accuracy of the account of how the commission was set
up and what subsequently happened.
Those who read the account, it is said, were shocked at the 'arrogant and
petulant' version of events. Sir David appeared more concerned that his
original recommendations had not been followed to the letter rather than
trying to assess what the commission had achieved.
Those who have read the Calcutt chapters believe they are biased. Commission
members note that when they gave evidence to Sir David they were not asked
how the body was working. Sir David was more concerned that it might have
strayed into areas such as defending press freedom.
In evidence to Sir David, the commission said self-regulation of the press
was working. Between January 1991 and July last year, 36 complaints or 3 per
cent of the total had been upheld. In 358 cases the commission found no
prima facie breach of the code of practice drawn up by the newspaper
industry. And 373 complaints were resolved between editor and complainant.
Only six complaints on breaches of privacy were upheld.
The newspaper industry will have a difficult job arguing that case in the
face of political anger over celebrated rows, particularly those involving
the royal family and the marriage of the Prince and Princess of Wales.
Perhaps the most notorious was about recorded telephone conversations,
apparently of the Princess of Wales talking to a male friend. They were not
only published in The Sun but 'exhibited' by it on a premium telephone line.
In spite of the growing furore in parliament and the second reading of the
private member's bill introduced by Mr Clive Soley, Labour MP for
Hammersmith, on the press at the end of this month, it is unlikely Calcutt's
draconian measures will be implemented.
What is now considered inevitable - and senior newspaper figures privately
agree - is the introduction of measures against the bugging and reproduction
of private telephone calls unless the public interest is involved.
