<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / Pre-birth technique decides calves' sex
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE first calves whose sex was pre-determined at conception have been born
in Cambridge, an Anglo-American scientific team will announce today.
The ability to choose a calf's gender, long sought by cattle breeders, is
likely to transform the economics and management of livestock production
worldwide.
The Holstein Friesian calves - three male and three female - are the product
of collaboration between Mastercalf, a Cambridge biotechnology company, the
Institute of Animal Physiology and Genetics Research in Cambridge, and the
US Department of Agriculture's Germplasm Physiology Laboratory in Maryland.
The scientists are producing pre-sexed calf embryos at a rate of more than
100 per week for use in large-scale field trials under way on farms in
England and Scotland.
If all goes well, sex determination will be available commercially within a
couple of years. Mr Barrie Audis, chairman of the British Cattle Breeders
Club, predicts it will make a big impact on the dairy and beef industries.
The technique depends on an instrument called a flow cytometer that sorts
bulls' sperm into two parts according to their genetic content. Sperm with
an X-chromosome result in female calves and those with a Y-chromosome give
males.
But the sorting process does not give enough sexed sperm for conventional
artificial insemination. Embryo transfer and in vitro fertilisation are
necessary - cows' eggs are fertilised in test tubes with the appropriate
sperm and the resulting embryos used to establish pregnancy.
Mr Geoff Mahon, Mastercalf managing director, said sex determination will be
combined with other techniques of genetic selection, so that bull calves can
be given the characteristics most desirable for beef production while
heifers retain the best genes for milking.
Male embryos will be most in demand, since beef farmers want only bull
calves and an average dairy farmer needs a ratio of one heifer calf to every
three bull calves sold for meat.
Mr Mahon says the cost of sex-guaranteed embryos is uncertain. Mr Audis, a
potential customer, says: 'I could justify buying an embryo for Pounds 50 to
Pounds 60 if I am guaranteed that it is a male beef calf.'
With a world population of dairy cattle of about 220m - about half of which
are born through artificial insemination - Mastercalf sees a large market
for the technology. It has already given Mitsubishi Corporation an exclusive
licence for Japan.
</TEXT>
<XX>
