<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / BBC to confirm choice of deputy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Bob Phillis, chief executive of Independent Television News, will be
confirmed today as the new deputy director-general of the BBC.
Mr Phillis, a former managing director of Central Independent Television and
former group managing director of Carlton Communications, is the most
important of the new appointments to be announced by Mr John Birt, who took
over as director-general on January 4. The new deputy director-general, who
is 47, will have the title of managing director of resources.
He will have control over the entire operational and financial structure of
the BBC and will be responsible for overseeing, at least for some time, the
corporation's international activities, including BBC World Service and
World Service Television.
Mr Phillis is not expected to join the BBC until the present restructuring
of ITN is complete. A seven-company consortium, led by Carlton
Communications, is due to take over from the existing 15 companies which own
the news organisation.
Ms Liz Forgan, the director of programmes at Channel 4 who has a reputation
as an independent-minded defender of broadcasting freedom, will join the BBC
as a managing director. Until now it had been assumed that she would become
managing director of BBC Television in succession to Mr Will Wyatt. There
were growing reports in the corporation last night that Ms Forgan would
become managing director of BBC Radio in succession to Mr David Hatch.
The managerial changes do not imply a big structural reorganisation at the
BBC, at least not immediately. Reports that the corporation was to become a
single-structure organisation covering both radio and television seem wide
of the mark.
Mr Phillis, who introduced tighter financial controls at ITN, will have the
task of improving financial disciplines at the much larger BBC. One of his
first tasks will be to get to the bottom of the admitted Pounds 38m
overspend at BBC Television in 1991-92 and the potential overspend of at
least Pounds 20m in 1992-93
The new managing director of resources will also be responsible for
overseeing the implementation of producer choice throughout BBC Television.
This is the policy that enables programme makers to buy services from the
outside market if it is more efficient.
</TEXT>
