<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / Weather blocks Shetland salvage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HEAVY seas and high winds around Shetland again blocked attempts to remove
the oil remaining on the tanker Braer yesterday.
Although the ship has not broken apart, salvage specialists believe this
will eventually happen.
Experts now believe that no further oil is leaking from the vessel, which
may still contain as much as half of its 84,000-tonne cargo. But oil is
still spreading northwards for about 25 miles up the west coast of the main
Shetland island.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, and Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary,
will both make statements to the Commons about the disaster today.
Yesterday Shetland salmon farmers received a boost when the supermarket
group Safeway said it would continue to buy farmed Shetland salmon after it
had visited the islands.
Last Friday Marks and Spencer announced that it was stopping buying Shetland
salmon as 'a temporary precautionary measure'. Other food retailers are
monitoring the situation.
The Shetland salmon farming industry is one of the sectors of the islands'
economy most threatened by the disaster. Since Friday the salmon farmers
have been prohibited from harvesting salmon in a 400,000 square mile area
under a ban ordered by the Scottish Office. The ban, which also covers the
catching of sea fish, was announced just after the islands' fishing and
fish-farming organisations had declared their own ban.
There are 16 salmon farms in the area covered by the ban, accounting for
about a quarter of Shetland's salmon production which last year totalled
10,000 tonnes.
Shetland council said yesterday that it was retaining the solicitors
Penningtons to represent it in dealing with legal issues arising from the
Braer incident.
</TEXT>
