<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / France 'ready to liberate camps'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Roland Dumas, the French foreign minister, said yesterday France was
prepared to act alone if necessary to liberate by force prisoner camps in
Bosnia where civilians had been raped and tortured.
'I suggest we ensure that this liberation is put into effect if necessary by
force, since we now have the legal right to intervene and there is evidence
on the existence of these camps and of tortures and rape that are committed
there,' Mr Dumas said on RTL radio.
He said he had asked Mr Bernard Kouchner, the health and humanitarian
affairs minister, to arrange 'if necessary on our own' for convoys under
military escort to go to the camps and liberate them.
Mr Dumas also said a UN resolution authorising the use of force to implement
a no-fly zone over Bosnia should be passed in the next few days.
'This means shooting down planes if necessary and a right of pursuit and
pre-emption if installations such as missile batteries or radars prevent
them from carrying out their mission,' he said.
Mr Kouchner earlier urged the UN to amend its arms embargo to allow the
Bosnians to arm themselves.
Mr Eduard Balladur, a favourite to become prime minister if the
conservatives win the elections, yesterday also urged the UN to act. 'The
time has come for vigorous intervention,' he said.
Mr Alija Izetbegovic, the Bosnian president, this weekend met President
Francois Mitterrand, who is said to have agreed to discuss the possibility
of intervention under the aegis of the UN.
</TEXT>
