<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 93 / Press complaints chief attacks self-regulation report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD McGREGOR of Durris, chairman of the Press Complaints Commission,
yesterday fiercely attacked the author of a government report on regulation
of the press, accusing him of bias and proposing censorship that threatened
to emasculate British journalism.
His attack follows reports that Sir David Calcutt QC, who was asked by the
government to investigate how well press self-regulation has worked in the
past two years, has recommended tough new controls. They are said to include
substantial fines for newspapers which breach a statutory code of practice,
a press complaints tribunal chaired by a judge and criminal offences of
physical trespass and electronic eavesdropping.
Sir David's report was delivered to Mr Peter Brooke, the National Heritage
Secretary, on Friday. Neither Mr Brooke nor senior officials from his
department would comment yesterday.
Lord McGregor yesterday accused Sir David of 'failing to give a proper
judicious assessment of the evidence submitted to him'. The PCC chairman
said the proposals would mean using the power of government to 'censor' the
press.
The growing alarm of the newspaper industry at Sir David's recommendations
seems to be based on a sight of a part of the report which deals with the
work of the PCC, the body that replaced the Press Council. This account is
critical and negative. The PCC in its evidence told Sir David it believed
self-regulation of the press was working well.
The reported recommendations for action are identical to those suggested by
Sir David Calcutt in his 1990 report for implementation should
self-regulation be seen to fail. Sir David was asked last June to carry out
a six month investigation into how self-regulation was working. During that
period there was criticism of alleged press intrusion into the private lives
of members of the royal family and government ministers.
Lord McGregor emphasised yesterday that in a long period of one party
government it was particularly important that the only effective opposition
 -the press - should not be emasculated.
Mr Clive Soley, the Labour MP whose private member's bill on the press
receives its second reading on January 29, said he thought the reported
proposals were excessive and would impede good investigative journalism.
The government plans to publish the Calcutt report later this month. Its
attitude to new press controls should become clearer during the second
reading of Mr Soley's right of reply bill.
Initial political reactions suggested the recommendations are seen as
extreme although there is growing support for some action against the
grosser forms of press intrusion. An end to bugging of private telephone
calls is most likely.
Showdown, Page 6
</TEXT>
