<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 93 / International Company News: Results at AMD are better than
expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ADVANCED Micro Devices, the US semiconductor manufacturer, reported
higher-than-expected fourth-quarter and year-end sales and earnings, boosted
by strong sales of its microprocessors to personal computer makers.
Fourth-quarter revenues rose 9 per cent to Dollars 400.2m from Dollars
366.2m while net income was Dollars 69.6m, before preferred stock dividends,
or 73 cents a share after the dividend. A year ago AMD reported net income
of Dollars 106.7m, or Dollars 1.17 a share, after the dividend. Net earnings
included a gain equivalent to 52 cents a share from the sale of shares of
Xilinx, another chip maker.
'AMD had an excellent quarter capping off an excellent year,' said Mr W. J.
Sanders, chairman and chief executive. Shipments of 386 microprocessors
surpassed 3m, a record for the company, he said.
For the year, AMD reported record sales of Dollars 1.5bn, an increase of 23
per cent over 1991.
Net income of Dollars 245m before the preferred stock dividend, and Dollars
2.57 a share after the dividend, also reached a new high for the company.
For 1991, revenues were Dollars 1.2bn and net income Dollars 145.3m, or
Dollars 1.53 a share, after the dividend.
AMD was recently forced to postpone plans to introduce a next-generation 486
microprocessor after an unfavourable court ruling in its intellectual
property disputes with Intel, the largest US chip maker.
